    "summary": "Los Millares was a Chalcolithic (Copper Age) settlement in southeastern Spain, near the present-day town of Santa Fe de Mondújar in Almería, occupied roughly from 3200 to 2200 BCE. The site comprised a fortified settlement with concentric stone walls, a large necropolis of collective passage tombs, and an extensive system of outlying forts and watchtowers, making it one of the most complex prehistoric settlements in western Europe.\n\nThe inhabitants of Los Millares practiced mixed farming, animal husbandry, and copper metallurgy, drawing on rich local ore deposits in the Sierra de Gádor. Grave goods from the tombs indicate long-distance exchange networks reaching the Mediterranean coast and beyond. The culture is associated with the broader phenomenon of Megalithic tomb building across Iberia and Atlantic Europe during this period. Los Millares eventually declined as the Bell Beaker culture spread across Iberia in the late third millennium BCE.",
